buginformation.description:
Created attachment 287375
                example project

                When evaluating a conditional breakpoint that involves an object that itself uses recursive generics, eclipse cannot evaluate the breakpoint and reports that the
                condition has compilation errors.

                Here is an example code (a project is attached):

                public class Main {

                public static void main(String[] args) {
                MyClass(?) cls = new MyClass()();
                System.out.println("x"); // add conditional breakpoint here (e.g. "cls.getBoolean()")
                }

                private static class MyClass(T extends MyClass(T)) {

                public boolean getBoolean() {
                return false;
                }
                }
                }

                Notice the recursive generic parameter of class MyClass. A conditional breakpoint like the one stated in the comment fails during debugging with the following error
                message:

                "Conditional breakpoint has compilation error(s).

                Reason:
                Evaluations must contain either an expression or a block of well-formed statements"

                The error log further contains the following warning:
                "Compile error during code evaluation: Bound mismatch: The type Object is not a valid substitute for the bounded parameter (T extends Main.MyClass(T)) of the type
                Main.MyClass(T)"

                No stack trace is available.

                Conditional breakpoints worked in situations like above at least until eclipse 4.15.

1, Create a class:

                public class ExpTest {
                record Record(String name, int age) {
                }

                void run() {
                var r = new Record("xxx", 5);
                System.out.println("r:" + r);
                }
                }

                2, Put a breakpoint into the run method, on the println-line
                3, Run the code
                4, Try to use the 'Expressions' view, but it fails, neither 'r.name' nor 'r.name()' works, and even 'r' or 'this' fails

                It seems, that Eclipse tries to parse the source file and construct a new 'skeleton' which contains all the relevant types for evaluating the user entered
                expression. However, this parsing and source-generating code is not compatible with Java 17 syntax, and it doesn't generate anything for records.

Sample 1:

                ```
                import java.util.function.Consumer;

                public class InspectLambda {

                public static void main(String[] args) {
                int number = 23;

                Consumer(Integer) myConsumer = (id) -) {
                System.out.println("id = " + id);
                System.out.println(); // Add a breakpoint here
                };
                myConsumer.accept(number);
                }
                }
                ```

                Stop at the lambda 'myConsumer', it can evaluate variables such as 'number', 'args' from enclosing method well.


                Sample 2:
                ```
                import java.util.ArrayList;
                import java.util.List;

                public class InspectLambdaOnChainCalls {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                int number = 23;
                List(String) users = new ArrayList(String)();
                users.add("a");

                users.stream().forEach(u -) {
                String localName = "local name";
                System.out.println("user name: " + u); // Add a breakpoint here
                });
                }
                }
                ```

                Stop at the lambda `System.out.println("user name: " + u)` of the chain calls, it cannot evaluate variables such as 'number', 'users' from enclosing method. But
                hovering at those variables, it can display their values well.


                Currently the evaluation engine collects variables for 3 frames starting from lambda, that works for the simple lambda calls. But for chain calls, there are more
                than 3 frames between the lambda frame and the enclosing method. That's why local variables of enclosing method are not recognized.

Created attachment 288101
                Screen recording showing the NPE occurring.

                I sporadically see the following exception and an error dialog when I try to debug code in: java.lang.ClassLoader.getDefinedPackage(String)

                java.lang.NullPointerException
                at org.eclipse.jdt.internal.debug.core.model.JDIStackFrame.updateVariables(JDIStackFrame.java:765)
                at org.eclipse.jdt.internal.debug.core.model.JDIStackFrame.getVariables0(JDIStackFrame.java:395)
                at org.eclipse.jdt.internal.debug.core.model.JDIStackFrame.getVariables(JDIStackFrame.java:307)
                at org.eclipse.debug.internal.ui.model.elements.StackFrameContentProvider.getAllChildren(StackFrameContentProvider.java:50)
                at org.eclipse.jdt.internal.debug.ui.variables.JavaStackFrameContentProvider.getAllChildren(JavaStackFrameContentProvider.java:36)
                at org.eclipse.debug.internal.ui.model.elements.StackFrameContentProvider.getChildCount(StackFrameContentProvider.java:29)
                at org.eclipse.debug.internal.ui.model.elements.ElementContentProvider.retrieveChildCount(ElementContentProvider.java:126)
                at org.eclipse.debug.internal.ui.model.elements.ElementContentProvider$2.run(ElementContentProvider.java:76)
                at org.eclipse.core.internal.jobs.Worker.run(Worker.java:63)


                See attached video: "npe_when_debugging_ClassLoader_getDefinedPackage.mp4"

                To reproduce:

                1. Create a Java project.
                2. Create 2 Java sources:

                package test;

                public class Test {

                public static void main(String[] args) {
                int x = 42;
                System.out.println("(1) x=" + x);
                SomeClass c = new SomeClass();
                c.foo();
                System.out.println("(1) x=" + x);
                }

                }

                package test;

                public class SomeClass {

                public void foo() {
                System.out.println("SomeClass.foo()");
                }
                }

                3. Set breakpoints:

                ClassLoader [line: 2241] - getDefinedPackage(String) - at "NamedPackage p = packages.get(name);"
                Test [line: 7] - main(String[]))) - at the 1st print in the snippet
                Test [line: 10] - main(String[])) - at the 2nd print in the snippet

                4. Debug the "Test.java" snippet.
                5. Resume until you see the error dialog and the exception in the Error Log view.

                Seen with:

                Eclipse SDK
                Version: 2022-03 (4.23)
                Build id: I20220216-1800

                Also seen with latest JDT.

It is possible to place a break-point in a lambda expression block like the "s1" lambda in the following example.
                But unfortunately it is not possible to place a breakpoint in a lambdas block if that lambda is nested in the other lambda like the "s2" or "s3" expressions below

                Supplier(String) s1= () -) {
                return "";
                };
                Supplier(Supplier(String)) s2= () -) () -) {
                return "";
                };
                Supplier(Supplier(Supplier(String))) s3= () -) () -) () -) {
                return "";
                };


                When I try to place a break-points in the line of the return statements of s2 or s3 the break-point is added to the method below instead. When both lambdas are
                converted to anonymous classes placing a break-point at the nested return works, but only if both Suppliers are classes, if only the inner one is a class creation
                it still does not work.

                My Eclipse version is 2022-03 M3 (4.23.0 M3), Build id: 20220224-1226 and I did not encounter this behaviour before so it could be a regression. I hope I have
                assigned the right Bugzilla Components.

Arrays.asList("a", "b", "c").stream().filter(s -) s.length() ) 0);
                Arrays.asList("a", "b", "c").stream().filter(s -) s.length() ) 0);

                Adding Lambda Entry Method breakpoint on both the lines does not work as it finds already a method breakpoint on same method.

Snippet provided by Vikas:

                interface Drawable{
                public void draw();
                }
                public class c {
                public static void main(String[] args) {
                int width=10;
                //with lambda
                Drawable d2=()-){ // Lambda entry breakpoint
                System.out.println("Drawing "+width);
                };
                d2.draw();
                }
                }

                Lambda entry breakpoint at the above mentioned line does not stop during debug run.
